ARPING(8)                      System Manager's Manual                  ARPING(8)

NAME
       arping - send ARP REQUEST to a neighbour host

SYNOPSIS
       arping [-AbDfhqUV] [-c count] [-w deadline] [-i interval]
              [-s source] [-I interface] {destination}

DESCRIPTION
       Ping destination on device interface by ARP packets, using
       source address source.

       arping is used to discover hosts on directly attached networks.
       Since ARP is a non-routable protocol, this only works for hosts
       on the same physical network (or broadcast domain).

OPTIONS
       -A     The same as -U, but uses ARP REPLY packets instead of
              ARP REQUEST. This is used to update other hosts' ARP
              caches after a failover.

       -b     Send only MAC level broadcasts. Normally arping starts
              from sending broadcast, and switches to unicast after
              reply received.

       -c count
              Stop after sending count ARP REQUEST packets. With
              deadline option (-w), instead wait for count ARP REPLY
              packets, or until the timeout expires.

       -D     Duplicate address detection mode. Used in IPv4LL.
              The exit code is 0 if the address is not in use
              (no reply received), and 1 if the address is already
              in use.

       -f     Finish after the first reply confirming that target is
              alive. Good for scripts that want to check host
              reachability.

       -h     Display help message and exit.

       -I interface
              Name of network device where to send ARP REQUEST
              packets.

       -i interval
              Specify an interval, in seconds, between packets
              (default is 1).

       -q     Quiet output. Nothing is displayed.

       -s source
              IP source address to use in ARP packets. If this option
              is absent, the source address is:
              - In DAD mode (-D): 0.0.0.0
              - Otherwise: the IP address of the interface

       -U     Unsolicited ARP mode. Updates neighbours' ARP caches.
              No replies are expected.

       -V     Print version of the program and exit.

       -w deadline
              Specify a timeout, in seconds, before arping exits
              regardless of how many packets have been sent or
              received.

EXIT STATUS
       The exit status is 0 if at least one reply was received. If
       no replies are received, the exit status is 1.

       In DAD mode (-D), the exit status is 0 if no reply was
       received (address is available), and 1 if a reply was received
       (address is already in use).

EXAMPLES
       arping -I eth0 192.168.1.1
              Send ARP requests to 192.168.1.1 via eth0.

       arping -c 3 192.168.1.1
              Send 3 ARP requests.

       arping -D -I eth0 192.168.1.100
              Check if 192.168.1.100 is in use (DAD).

       arping -f 192.168.1.1
              Quit on first reply.

       arping -U -s 192.168.1.100 -I eth0 192.168.1.100
              Send gratuitous ARP to update neighbours.

       arping -w 5 -c 10 host
              Send 10 probes with 5-second deadline.

SEE ALSO
       ping(8), arp(8), ifconfig(8)

